#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:1
msgid "Lemmy on Separate Subdomains"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:3
msgid ""
"This guide details hosting the Lemmy backend and frontend on different "
"domains. This is useful, for example, if you want users to have a webfinger "
"(user handle) without a subdomain, but want to host services on the same "
"domain."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:5
msgid ""
"As a general overview, this works by handling federation requests on the "
"short domain and forwarding them to the Lemmy backend. API and frontend "
"requests however are handled on the long domain."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:7
msgid "Placeholders"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:9
msgid ""
"`short.domain` represents the shortened domain you would like to use for "
"user handles."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:10
msgid ""
"`sub.longerdomain.com` represents the domain where the UI will be served."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:11
msgid ""
"The `proxy` network is the configured Traefik network, and is only "
"referenced in the Traefik configuration. Please see the [Traefik "
"documentation](https://doc.traefik.io/traefik/providers/docker/#network)."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:12
msgid ""
"The `backend` network is the network used to communicate between Docker "
"containers. This is only referenced in the Traefik configuration. This can "
"be renamed to your liking. In the configuration, this is referenced as an "
"`external` Docker network, but can also be an `internal` Docker network "
"([documentation here](https://docs.docker.com/compose/how-tos/networking/"
"#use-a-pre-existing-network))."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:14
msgid "Limitations"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/separate_subdomains.md:16
msgid ""
"If there is another service using the `/api`, `/pictrs`, `/feeds`, `/"
"nodeinfo`, `/.well-known`, `/inbox`, `/version`, and `/sitemap.xml` paths on "
"`short.domain`, it will conflict with the Lemmy server. Similarly, if there "
"is a service on `short.domain` listening for the `Accept: application/"
"activity+json` HTTP header, it will also conflict with the Lemmy server."
msgstr ""

